    ğŸ“¦ OSI Model â€“ 7 Layer Network Architecture
        ğŸ”¹ Full Form: OSI = Open Systems Interconnection
        ğŸ”¹ Introduced by: ISO (International Standards Organization) in late 1970s
        ğŸ”¹ Purpose: To standardize network communication between heterogeneous systems
        ğŸ”¹ Type: Conceptual model, not a protocol
        ğŸ”¹ Benefit: Interoperability, modularity, flexibility

    ğŸ“š 7 Layers of OSI Model (Bottom to Top)
        Layer | Name         | Function (Keyword)                   | Data Unit
            1 | Physical     | Transmission of raw bits             | Bits
            2 | Data Link    | Framing, error detection, MAC        | Frame
            3 | Network      | Routing, logical addressing (IP)     | Packet
            4 | Transport    | End-to-end delivery, segmentation    | Segment
            5 | Session      | Establish/Manage/Terminate sessions  | Data
            6 | Presentation | Encryption, compression, translation | Data
            7 | Application  | User interface, network services     | Data

    ğŸ”„ Working Mechanism
        Each layer on the sender side:
            â¤ Adds its own header (H) (and sometimes trailer)
            â¤ Passes it to the layer below
            At receiver:
            â¤ Each layer removes its respective header, processes info, and passes up.
            This process = Encapsulation & De-encapsulation

        ğŸ”— Layer Communication
            Peer-to-peer communication:
            Each layer on device A talks logically to the same layer on device B via a protocol.

            Adjacent layer communication (interface):
            Layers interact directly within the same device using well-defined interfaces.

        ğŸ§± Layer Groups
            Group               | Layers        | Purpose
            Network Support     | 1 â€“ 2 â€“ 3     | Data movement across devices
            User Support        | 5 â€“ 6 â€“ 7     | App-level communication
            Transition Layer    | 4 (Transport) | Links user & network support layers

       âš™ï¸ Key Concepts
            Encapsulation:  Wrapping data with headers/trailers as it moves down the layers
            Decapsulation: Unwrapping headers/trailers as data moves up the layers
            Only Layers 1â€“3 are used by intermediate nodes (routers/switches).

        ğŸ” Mnemonic to Remember Layers (Top to Bottom):
        "All People Seem To Need Data Processing"
        Application â€“ Presentation â€“ Session â€“ Transport â€“ Network â€“ Data Link â€“ Physical

